d routed to appropriate subsequent therapy paths [Data: Entities (126, 135, 67); Relationships (364, 367, 398, 399, +more)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Management of recurrence involves escalation to second- and third-line therapies.\",\n      \"explanation\": \"For patients exhibiting progression, incomplete resection, or positive biopsy results after initial management, escalation to second-line therapy (SEM-6) or third-line therapy (SEM-8) is systematically outlined. This escalation is detailed in relationships stemming from the SEM-5 and SEM-7 entities, with specific criteria for when patients should advance along these regimens. The management pathways stress that both pathological and radiographic progression are indicators for moving beyond surveillance into active, escalated therapy [Data: Entities (134, 144, 136, 145, 137); Relationships (343, 345, 387, 389, 363, +more)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Biopsy and resection status affect subsequent management choices.\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Biopsy findings and whether a mass has been completely resected heavily influence next steps. If a mass is positive for viable seminoma, or if resection is incomplete, patients are pushed toward more aggressive therapy or considered for adjunct chemotherapy. Complete resection with negative pathology may lead to surveillance or adjuvant therapy depending on risk stratification. The protocol’s decisional relationships ensure that residual disease is neither overlooked nor overtreated [Data: Entities (131, 132, 133, 143, 141, 142); Relationships (360, 362, 366, 396, 399, +more)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Progressive disease is a high-risk indicator mandating immediate action.\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Patients with evidence of progressive disease, as defined by growing masses or rising tumor markers post-therapy, are directly routed to second-line therapy. These cases are linked in the community through actionable relationships tha